           </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>A Special Note about Children</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>We encourage everyone to visit the University Site and learn about the University. Children, however, are not eligible to register to use the services of the University, and we ask that minors not submit any personal information to us. If you are a minor, you may use this service only in conjunction with a parent or guardian. Parents or guardians should become knowledgeable about software and other tools so they can assure that childrens use of the Internet reflects parental preferences and requirements.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>Security</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>Although the University Site has certain security measures in place to protect the loss, misuse, and alteration of the information you provide, no email or web transmission is completely secure against interception or incorrect routing. Thus, there is always the risk that unauthorized persons may access or use your personally identifiable information.  If you are worried because your communication is very sensitive, do not send it electronically. Please consider this prior to submitting any information to us via the University Site. You use the University Site and send us such information at your own risk.</p>\r\n                            <p>Although we take reasonable measure to protect your privacy on the University Site, we need your help.  You have control over your own privacy. Think carefully before providing any personal or financial information online. If you desire to remain anonymous when you write to us or send us submissions you should not tell us your name, the names of other users, or of your friends. To fully protect your privacy, you should try to exclude any information that you think may identify you or others.</p>\r\n                            <p>Remember that we cannot protect your privacy once you leave the University Site, such as by hyperlink. We do not control the privacy policies of other websites. So when you visit other websites, check each sites privacy policy, and be careful about the information you submit or share. In addition, you should only forward our email messages or other website information (such as our job postings) to others through the buttons or links provided within the email or the University Site. When you use your email systems forwarding capabilities, others may be able to take actions in your name and/or access your personal information.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n            </div>', 'Privacy Statement', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'privacy-statement', '', '', '2016-02-11 20:25:02', '2016-02-11 20:25:02', '', 0, 'http://localhost/life-measures-wordpress/?page_id=222', 0, 'page', '', 0),
	(224, 1, '2015-03-05 03:08:13', '2015-03-05 03:08:13', '<body id="indices" class="page page-id-15 page-parent page-template page-template-page-indices-php win8 chrome chrome-0">\r\n        <section class="intro-image" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/cki-template11-headers-indicies.jpg&#39;);">\r\n            <header>\r\n                <h1>Constructing the Quality of Life Measures</h1>\r\n                <hr>\r\n            </header>\r\n        </section>\r\n        <div id="content">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n                <a name="constructing-the-indices"></a>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                        <h2 id="contstructing_the_indices">Constructing the Measures</h2>\r\n                        <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>Drawing on a long history of literature, beginning with ancient Greek philosophical works and ending with modern economic and psychological empirical studies, the Quality of Life Initiative defines wellbeing or quality of life as consisting of two parts: happiness, understood as the range of positive feelings stretching from contentment to joy that a person experiences at any given time, and life satisfaction, understood as a cognitive evaluation of ones life as a whole. Additionally, our research has found that personal wellbeing derives largely from two broad sources: livability, the external factors that inhibit or enable Quality of Life, and life ability, the internal capabilities that allow individuals to enjoy and master their environment.</p>\r\n                            <p><strong>Issues of Data-availability across countries does that the Quality of Life Measures capture livability slightly better than they capture lifeability.</strong></p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <a name="statistical-analysis"></a>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2 id="statistical_analysis">Statistical Analysis</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>The literature review and empirical meta-analysis identified an initial set of recurring variables found to impact happiness and life satisfaction (see the Initiatives literature reviews here). A Principal Component Analysis of approximately one hundred variables in the World Values Survey was used to identify the underlying attributes of these factors. The complete set of factors identified through this analysis was incorporated in an Ordinary Least Squares regression and A Structural Equation Model controlling for other factors. The analysis revealed a set of variables with a significant positive impact on Quality of Life. These findings were subjected to several forms of sensitivity analysis. The significant factors and controls were grouped together in six dimensions according to their weights and theoretical considerations to form the six dimensions of Quality of Life.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <a name="creating-and-validating-the-dimensions"></a>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2 id="creating_and_validation_the_dimensions">Creating and Validating the Dimensions</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>The six dimensions WERE RECONSTRUCTED using a combination of self-reported and objective indicators to correct for the disadvantages of each. The specific indicators were chosen based on statistical analysis, previous findings in the literature, comparability across time and geography, availability, and source reputation in order to ensure the highest possible level of quality. Because previous research has found that outcomes relative to expectations are strong predictors of Quality of Life, changes in some variables were selected in addition to actual levels.</p>\r\n                            <p>The indicators selected were tested analytically through Confirmatory Factor Analysis, Average Variance Extracted, and the Cronbachs Alpha method.</p>\r\n                            <p>Indicators were normalized using an approach modeled on the Human Development Index from the United Nations. Goalposts were chosen to represent the maximum and minimum values for each indicator, either from the source or from an analysis of the data. Individual scores were calculated using a linearization between the two goalposts. Once the scores for indicators were obtained, they were aggregated hierarchically, with each score equaling either the score of the associated indicator or the average of the scores one level below it. The score for Dimension 1 is therefore the average of the score for Components 1A and 1B while the score for Component 1A is the average of the score for Subcomponents 1Ai and 1Aii.</p>\r\n                            <p>Additional research and analysis relative to the project can be found <a href="<?php echo home_url(); ?>/learn-about-the-research">here</a>.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n            </div>\r\n            <a name="dimensions"></a>\r\n            <section class="carousel dimensions constructing-the-measures">\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n                <header class="title-group">\r\n                    <h2 id="six_dimensions">Six Dimensions of Quality of Life Measures</h2>\r\n                    <hr/>\r\n                    <p>\r\n                        The Quality of Life Measures compiled data from a whole host of sources to compose this United States measurements. Various sources include (but are not limited to) the World Bank, Freedom House, Center for Systemic Peace, U.S. Census, the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Gallup, and the National Center for Educational Statistics.\r\n                    </p>\r\n                </header>\r\n                <div class="slide-toggle clearfix">\r\n                    <a href="#" class="us selected">U.S. Measurements</a><a href="#" class="world">World Measurements</a>\r\n                </div>\r\n                <ul class="slide-list">\r\n                    <li class="slide us">\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns-no-padding opportunity">\r\n                            <div class="title">\r\n                                <div class="image-container">\r\n                                    <img id="symbol-rounded" src="<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/dimensions_symbol/Symbol_Opportunity.png">\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <h3>Opportunity</h3>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="dimension-components">\r\n                                <h4>Poverty</h4>\r\n                                <h4>Employment</h4>\r\n                                <h4>Community Vitality</h4>\r\n                                <h4>Education</h4>\r\n           